In this work, we explore approaches for constraining the behavior of depression detection methods by the presence of symptoms known to be related to depression, like mood and sleep issues.
To do so, we develop nine symptom detection models that correspond to questions present in PHQ9, a screening questionnaire that has been clinically validated and commonly used in practical setting [kroenke2001phq]. These questions ask how often the patient has experienced symptoms from nine symptom groups (e.g., how often have you had ``little interest/pleasure in doing things?'').